<p>The <code>dir</code> tag provides a simple directory listing using PHP's scandir.</p>

<h2>Basic Directory Listing</h2>
<pre>{open}dir APP . 'fragments/claude'{close}
  {open}$value{close}
{open}/dir{close}</pre>
<ul>
{dir APP . 'fragments/claude', rows=10}
  <li>{$value}</li>
{/dir}
</ul>
<p><em>(showing first 10 entries)</em></p>

<h2>List Application Root</h2>
<pre>{open}dir APP{close}
  {open}$value{close}
{open}/dir{close}</pre>
<ul>
{dir APP, rows=10}
  <li>{$value}</li>
{/dir}
</ul>
<p><em>(showing first 10 entries)</em></p>

<h2>Comparison: dir vs files</h2>
<table>
  <tr><th>Feature</th><th>dir</th><th>files</th></tr>
  <tr><td>Simplicity</td><td>Simple</td><td>Feature-rich</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Filtering</td><td>None</td><td>mask, onlyFiles, onlyDirs</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Recursion</td><td>No</td><td>Yes (recursive option)</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Properties</td><td>$value only</td><td>$path, $file, $item, $ext, $dir</td></tr>
  <tr><td>Base path</td><td>Manual</td><td>base option (app, data, pad)</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>Note</h2>
<p>The <code>dir</code> tag returns raw scandir output, which includes <code>.</code> and <code>..</code> entries. Use the <code>files</code> tag for more control over the listing.</p>
